// TEST: exec_self_return
// EXPECT: output "doubled=42;sum=63"
// EXPECT: targets js, ts, python, rust, go
//
// Regression fixture for Q-self-subst (codegen-completeness): an impl block
// that writes `Self` in its OWN method signature. Runs on ALL FIVE targets.
//
// `Doubler.doubled(self) -> Self` writes `Self` in *return* position, and
// `Doubler.add(self, other: Self) -> Int` writes `Self` in *parameter*
// position. Before the checker fix (P2), the impl method's own registered
// signature kept `Named("Self")` (only trait-declared method types were
// substituted), so both call sites hit E4001 (`Named("Self")` vs
// `Named("Doubler")`). The checker now substitutes `Self` -> the impl's target
// type across each impl method's params and return type at registration.
//
// The two codegen gaps that previously omitted ts/go are now both fixed:
//   * Go (P3, #144): rendered a `TypeSelf` outside a *trait*-impl method as the
//     `/* Self */` placeholder (`go.rs` set `go_self_subst` only when
//     `use_value_receiver` is true), emitting an invalid Go signature. Fixed by
//     setting `go_self_subst` for ALL impl methods.
//   * TS (P4): lowered `Self` to the `this` type, but the impl methods are
//     assigned to `Doubler.prototype = function(...): this { … }`; `tsc` only
//     permits a `this` type inside a class/interface member, so it rejected it
//     (TS2526). Fixed by setting `trait_self_subst` to the concrete target for
//     ALL impl methods.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

record Doubler {
  value: Int
}

impl Doubler {
  fn doubled(self) -> Self {
    Doubler { value: self.value + self.value }
  }

  fn add(self, other: Self) -> Int {
    self.value + other.value
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let d: Doubler = Doubler { value: 21 }
  let bigger: Doubler = d.doubled()
  let extra: Doubler = Doubler { value: 21 }
  println("doubled=${bigger.value};sum=${bigger.add(extra)}")
}
